charities including smiletrain in  at age  wang launched computer associates using credit cards for funding wang grew computer associates into one of the countrys largest software vendors wang has authored two books to help executives master technology techno vision  mcgrawhill and techno vision ii  mcgrawhill wang retired from computer associates in  he is an active philanthropist working with such organizations as smile train the world childhood foundation the islanders children’s foundation and the national center for missing and exploited children among others contents  early life  new york islanders  philanthropy  computer associates  awards and honors  long island residence  see also  references  external links early lifeedit charles b wang was born in shanghai to parents kenneth and mary wang charles has two brothers anthony w wang and francis wang his father was a supreme court judge in the republic of china the wangs moved to queens new york when he was eight years old he attended brooklyn technical high school in fort greene brooklyn wang earned a bachelor of science degree from queens college and began his computer career at columbia universitys riverside research institute new york islandersedit charles wang is a minority owner of the new york islanders hockey franchise of which he had become a partowner in  and majority owner from  he later bought out the share of business partner sanjay kumar in  and acquired the original iowa barnstormers arena football league franchise moving them to long island and renaming them the new york dragons wang’s sometimes unorthodox decisions as owner have received a mixture of praise and criticism according to former islanders general manager mike milbury wang “assumed that nobody could put a goal past a sumo wrestler” milbury said that “he was a man of his word a guy who desperately wanted to keep the team on the island” wang initially had a willingness to spend money with the goal of making the islanders competitive however recent team payrolls have decreased as the islanders failed to reach the playoffs between the – and – seasons wang hired neil smith as the islanders general manager during the  stanley cup finals but  days later smith was fired due to his unwillingness to adhere to the management by committee style of wang wang then gave the job to garth snow who subsequently retired from his playing position as the teams backup goaltender wang said that philosophical differences were the basis for firing smith this series of personnel moves combined with wang’s approval of longterm contracts for alexei yashin and goaltender rick dipietro several years later inspired a critical reaction from hockey journalists milbury reported that he had to talk wang out of giving michael peca a tenyear deal a forbes article investigated why certain nhl franchises could remain profitable despite poor attendance and overall league unprofitability they found that several league owners underreported their cable broadcast revenue they specifically accused wang of excluding half of the  million paid to the islanders for the  cable broadcast season wang made numerous efforts to build a new arena in nassau county as the veterans memorial coliseum was the secondoldest active arena and the islanders lease ended in  he was the master developer of the lighthouse project a property transformation of the nassau coliseum and surrounding  acres  km the project was to include a fivestar hotel condominiums an athletic complex featuring four ice rinks a basketball facility and a stateoftheart health club that would have served as the islanders’ practice facility and also be open to the public the development would also have included a sports technology center openair plaza and conference center the project was deemed to be too large by town of hempstead supervisor kate murray who made a counterproposal that was about half the size of what wang had originally intended wang balked at murrays proposal and decided to try to finance the building of a new arena for the islanders with public funds rather than paying for it himself as part of the lighthouse project in may  wang along with nassau county started an day campaign for a  million bond to fund a new arena for the islanders on august   the proposal was defeated by a margin of  to  wang has stated that he would not have bought the team if he knew how difficult it would be and would not do so if he could choose again a new york times article detailed wang’s “desperate” attempts to keep the team on long island ultimately however wang was unable to secure a renovated or new arena in uniondale jeff wilpon the coo of major league baseballs new york mets discussed the possibility of buying the islanders from wang and moving them adjacent to the mets home ballpark citi field in flushing queens there were also reports that businessman nelson peltz wanted to buy the islanders from wang and move them to barclays center in brooklyn on october   wang announced that the islanders would move to barclays center in  after the end of their lease at the nassau veterans memorial coliseum in various interviews wang said that “it was brooklyn or out of town” despite the move the franchise will remain named as the new york islanders and they are geographically still on long island in august  the nhl announced that wang had agreed to sell a substantial minority interest in the team to a group of investors and that the group would be transitioning to majority ownership in two years philanthropyedit wang is an active philanthropist and in  established the charles b wang foundation with the goal of donating to numerous charities that focused on bettering the lives of children and the disenfranchised he has worked with such causes as smile train the world childhood foundation the plainview chinese cultural center and the national center for missing and exploited children among others his donation of over  million to the state university of new yor